4.75/5  rDev +0.8%look: 4.75 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.75Thishops4u, May 03, 2016
4.7/5  rDev -0.2%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.75750ml cork and caged bottle with golden foil. Batch 1, 2015. Served within a lambic cradle, in a stemmed glass 4/30/2016.
Pours a medium straw yellow body, clear and remarkably effervescent with a nice thick 1 finger white head, with a good bit of retention time, a bit of lacing. Essentially looks similar to Oude Geuze. Smells of intense musty funk, oak, with a subtle background dark fruit sweetness not unlike sherry. Wheat, a bit of cracker and peppercorn. Mildly floral notes shine through. The intensity of the funk on the aroma is off the charts and maintains this as the beer warms up, it's quite impressive. Flavour is really quite nice in terms of complexity. Let's get this out of the way- it's not simply Oude Geuze. As on the nose, the funk is racheted up to a 11. Heavy must, damp oak, hay. It's incredibly rich and wholesome on top of the base lambic, which also provides a mild sweetness to it. That being said, there is a nice rich dark fruit, amaretto-like presence lingering in the background, seemingly evanescent but I seem to notice it more on the mouthfeel and finish. The mouthfeel is heavier bodied than most lambic; it actually reminds me a fair bit of 50N4E in how the body just feels a bit more substantial, with the same amount of carbonation, which is just about right in that it doesn't get prickly, but it never quite gets flat either. It just maintains very well with each sip one to savor, to smell and to taste. It seems to change a lot over time, especially the amount of sherry that comes out, but it doesn't lose that intensity. Overall- an incredibly funky lambic with a constantly fleeting yet stable background of sherry and amaretto, it's there and you know it, but you reach out for it and never quite grasp it. It's an unique lambic, like no other that I've had. This is a real intense ride, and I recommend enjoying your glass slowly and allowing it to decant on its own over time. 1,928 charactersStevedore, May 02, 2016
