4.77/5  rDev +1.3%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 5Big Poppy brought over this one for Slosh Fest 2015 a few weeks ago. Good fun gents! This was definitely a highlight of the day. 
From a 750 into a snifter
APPEARANCE: Pours a small, medium looking white head with decent retention. Head slowly fades to a faint wisp and ring. Clear gamboge orange in color with no real carbonation evident. A slight wisp remains until the end and leaves dots of lacing down the glass. 
SMELL: Bold nose of funky and barnyard aromas, hay, citrus notes, lemon and lime, as well as some floral elements. Very forthcoming and enticing. 
TASTE: Soft, funky with citrus notes up front. Hay and barnyard flavors at the finish with sour lemon tartness as well. A milder yet persistent finish of citrus fruit, tart lemon sourness, funky flavors with barnyard and wet grass lingering on the palate. Some floral notes as well, adding a touch of bitterness. Really nice and void of any real musty character. Not acidic at all either. Really smooth and refreshing. 
PALATE: Medium body and lower levels of carbonation. Creamy smooth on the palate, goes down fine and finishes very dry. Some tart lemon lingers on the palate. 
OVERALL: This was a real treat. Absolutely delicious, soft and flavorful. Lots of funky notes and tart lemon and citrus qualities here, without too much musty, dank character. Absolutely not acidic at all either, which makes it very soft, smooth and easy to drink. Extremely enjoyable and would love to drink this again. Big thanks to Poppy for bringing this one over. Didn't think I'd get to try this one. Cheers! 1,566 charactersJeffo, Feb 22, 2016
4.9/5  rDev +4%look: 5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 5 |  overall: 575cl bottle at the 3 Fonteinen Restaurant-Cafe (Beersel, Belgium)
White pepper, orange peels, oak, and glorious glorious PX sherry on the nose. Fine, the sherry is rather subtle at first, but it's unmistakably there. The oak is rather resilient even with the passage of time, with more of the sweetness from the sherry emerging as the beer decants. One thing that separates this brew from the other 3F offerings I've been able to try is that it seems to have an enhanced sort of mineral-y character to it (from the Oloroso barrels, maybe?) that I can't quite put a finger around, but in an awesome way.
The flavor is slightly more complex on the tongue than it is on the nose. The citrus is present, but in a rather shy fashion. Sharp white pepper and sweet sherry flavors dominate, with subtle hints of molasses and raisin seeping out when you rest it on the tongue. I know my description doesn't make it seem that way, but this is still unmistakably a Drie Fonteinen gueuze; the signature sourness and oak characters (horse blanket, leather, barnyard, etc.) are well-pronounced but far from being harsh and astringent.
The beer rolls off effortlessly on the palate and finishes mildly dry. To emulate almost every other 3F review ever written: quite musty, indeed.
Overall, a very unique brew that probably benefits more from the hype and the limited availability than it should; whereas it didn't quite bridge the gap between the worlds of gueuze and wine as mindblowingly as I expected it to, it did accomplish said task seemingly effortlessly. 1,552 charactersamano_h, Feb 19, 2016
